citeinfo.title: National Atlas of the United States

descript.abstract: This line dataset represents streams in the Conterminous United States. All feature classes are vertically integrated with each other and with 1:1,000,000-scale transportation and boundary data sets.
descript.purpose: This dataset is intended for researchers, students, and policy makers for reference and mapping purposes, and may be used for basic applications such as viewing, querying, and map output production, or to provide a basemap to support graphical overlays and analysis with other spatial data.
descript.supplinf: This data was originally stored in a geodatabase. All feature classes are vertically integrated with each other and with 1:1,000,000-scale transportation and boundary data sets.

attr.attrdef: A unique identifier for the 'reach' of the stream. ?The first eight digits are the Watershed Boundary Dataset 8-digit Hydrologic Unit Code, which identifies the subbasin in which the stream is located. The next six digits are randomly assigned, sequential numbers that are unique within a subbasin, resulting in a 14-character value. ?This attribute links features back to the National Hydrography Dataset, National Hydrography Dataset Plus, and other data sets that use reach codes.

A value that uniquely identifies each feature in the Medium-Resolution NHDFlowline feature class. This attribute links features to feature classes and tables in the Medium-Resolution National Hydrography Dataset and in NHDPlus. Because many features were split, there may be multiple features with the same value.
Unique from-node identifier. It represents the upstream end of a stream segment.
Unique to-node identifier. It represents the downstream end of a stream segment
An indication of whether a feature can participate in a geometric network.

attr.attrdef: A number representing the order of the stream using the Strahler stream order classification system, in which first-order streams have no tributaries, second-order streams begin at the confluence of two first order streams, third-order streams begin at the confluence of two second-order streams and so on. If a lower-order stream flows into a higher-order stream, the stream order of the higher-order stream does not increase.
